    <title>Combined summary - Drivechain -- Request for Discussion</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T01:03:54.078748+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-May/014394.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The bitcoin-dev mailing list is currently discussing various technical details of Bitcoin's sidechain technology and the proposed two-way pegged sidechain system, drivechains. The use of OP_BRIBE as a way to allow miners to be paid in exchange for their help in guaranteeing that a sidechain block is added to the largest chain is also discussed. The proposal for the process of transactions using OP_BRIBE_VERIFY involves sidechain miners broadcasting transactions with an OP_BRIBE output, which ends up in the memory pool of miners and is added to their next block. There is also discussion on the vulnerability of sidechains to theft and the need for restrictions on the amount of coin transferred from the side chain to the main chain.The Drivechain proposal, which enables a hybrid model where both a federation and miners provide acknowledgements of the sidechain state, is being supported by users, businesses, and developers. Another economic model being discussed is BMM (Bitcoin Meta Transactions), which is similar to Bitcoin's Proof-of-Work. In addition, there are conversations on the commitment structure for the coinbase transaction in drivechain implementation. In discussions about the security risks of implementing sidechains, concerns have been raised about the potential vulnerability of sidechains to theft, as a rich attacker could buy the entire reserve of a sidechain by paying the timeout multiplied by average transaction fees. CryptAxe suggests locking a sidechain miner’s funds to a particular bitcoin height and allowing the miner to reclaim the funds if they are not included in that block. Additionally, there are questions about the use cases for drivechains and why those use cases cannot be done in a much safer client-side validation fashion.The email conversation also discusses the use of OP_BRIBE as a way to allow miners to be paid in exchange for their help in guaranteeing that a sidechain block is added to the largest chain. There are concerns about the security of drivechains, with some arguing that the security model is dubious. User-activated soft-forks are proposed to ensure drivechains fail, and there is discussion around ways to involve miners as little as possible in the consensus.In an email exchange, Paul Sztorc discussed the potential security risks of implementing sidechains. The discussion begins with a concern about the possibility of an unlikely chance where h* to be put in the coinbase turns out to be 0, resulting in the rejection of OP_NOP4 by old nodes. Overall, the discussions revolve around the technical details and potential security risks of implementing sidechains and drivechains.A new proposal has been made by Paul Sztorc, creator of the decentralized prediction market platform, and it's called "Bitcoin Merged Mining" or BMM. The idea behind this is to incentivize miners to validate sidechains even if they are not running the actual sidechain software. However, Peter Todd, a Bitcoin core developer, responded that the security properties of BMM are much weaker than what he had proposed in ZooKeyv. It remains to be seen how these concerns will be addressed and whether BMM will be implemented in the future.</summary>
